:
* [https://books.google.com/books?id=9GECAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA217&dq=%22blizzer%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9MrJVJHZN8zeoASjmoCYCg&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=%22blizzer%22&f=false Thomas Ratcliffe of Worksop, Nottinghamshire, in the March 17, 1888, edition]

BLIZZARD (7th S. v. 106).—The word blizzard is well known through the Midlands, and its cognates are fairly numerous. I have known the word and its kin fully thirty years. Country folk use the word to denote blazing, blasting, blinding, dazzling, or stifling. One who has had to face a severe storm of snow, hail, rain, dust, or wind, would say on reaching shelter that he has "faced a blizzer," or that the storm was "a regular blizzard." A blinding flash of lightning would call forth the exclamation, "My! that wor a blizzomer!" or "That wor a blizzer!" "Put towthry sticks on th' fire, an let's have a blizzer"—a blaze. "A good blizzom" = a good blaze. "That tree is blizzared" = blasted, withered. As an oath the word is often used, and "May I be blizzerded" will be readily understood.
:
* A check of some of the Midlands regional glossaries printed in the 1800s finds several entries for blizzy. First, from Anne Baker, Glossary of Northamptonshire words and phrases (1854): <ref>{{cite book|author=Anne Baker|title=Glossary of Northamptonshire words and phrases vol. 1|date=1854|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=be8IAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA57&dq=%22Blizzy%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=StrJVMTOGszzoAS6l4Jw&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=%22Blizzy%22&f=false|page=57|access-date=Feb 21, 2015|isbn=1152470914}}</ref> 

BLIZZY. A blaze. "Blow the fire, and let's have a nice blizzy." This, though now considered a vulgarism, is a retention of the original A.-Sax. blysa, a blaze.

And Angelina Parker, A Glossary of Words Used in Oxfordshire (1876): <ref>{{cite book|author=Angalina Parker|title=A Glossary of Words Used in Oxfordshire|date=1876|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iIAHAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA114&dq=%22Blizzy%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=StrJVMTOGszzoAS6l4Jw&ved=0CCEQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=%22Blizzy%22&f=false|page=114|access-date=Feb 21 2015|isbn=117864894X}}</ref> 

Blizzy, a flaring fire produced by putting on small sticks. Ex. 'Let's 'a a bit of a blizzy afore us goes to bed.' 

And from Barzillai Lowsley, A Glossary of Berkshire Words and Phrases (1888): <ref>{{cite book|author=Barzillai Lowsley|title=A Glossary of Berkshire Words and Phrases|date=1888|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HKITAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA50&dq=%22Blizzy%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-NnJVOiGK5TVoASR_IHYCA&ved=0CFUQ6AEwCg#v=onepage&q=%22Blizzy%22&f=false|page=80|access-date=Feb 21 2015|isbn=1248484231}}</ref>

BLIZZY.— A blaze. The fire is said to be all of a "blizzy" when pieces of wood have been inserted amongst the coal to make it burn cheerfully. 

And from G. F. Northall,  A Warwickshire Word-book (1896): <ref>{{cite book|author=G. F. Northall|title=A Warwickshire Word-book|date=1896|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zy4_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA31&dq=%22Blizzy%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-NnJVOiGK5TVoASR_IHYCA&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=%22Blizzy%22&f=false|page=31|access-date=Feb 21 2015}}</ref>

Blizzy, sb. A blaze, a blast, a flare of fire. A.-Sax. blysa, a blaze. Common.

They suggest that blizzy survived from the ancient word blysa in numerous localities and might well share a root with the U.S. blizzard. 
